In 32 years, this is the only photo of my father and I having a laugh. In reality, I'm actually having a cry and he's having a laugh. 

A few seconds after this photo was taken and everyone had left the room, I looked at him and said "Once upon a time there was a point in my life where the last thing I wanted was to sit and play accordion with you, and now as i get older it's the thing I look most forward to" 

All he did back was smile and nod and said "See, now you know"...

71 years of bottled up emotions will make you tough in even to the most touching and loving moments lol 

But it was enough for me.

In this photo is some serious Canadian comedy royalty. On my right is the and only Tom Green, I've been lucky enough to do Massey Hall with him and Yuk Yuks countless times and each time he's as kind and humble as anyone in the business can be. And to my right is legendary comedy club owner Howard Wagman!!! Howard's been managing comedy clubs since his 20s and gave people like Harland Williams and Tom Green their start!! 

But the most important story here is that Howard was the person who discovered Norm Macdonald! If you know me personally you know that Norm Macdonald is a top 10 comic for me, and famously Howard chased down Norm after he bombed as a teenager and told him to not give up and to come back the next week and try again.

Within 5 years Norm would leave Ottawa and become a part of Saturday Night Live, Billy Madison, and every other thing in the 90s. 

Ottawa comedy and, most importantly, Canadian comedy has a lot of thanks to give to the two dudes in this photo. Fantastic night of comedy and blessed to be able to spend St.Pattys' day having a laugh with them.

I could quit comedy today and be happy for the rest of my life. When I was 16, I could have never imagined one day I'd be here. Sometimes people ask me what it's like moving from the city to the country. Photos like this make it easy to explain that there's a calm and beauty that helps you remember everything's gonna be ok. 

When I lived in the city, I always had constant anxiety, like I wasn't doing enough, it was always go, go, go.... 
Since moving up north, that feeling goes away, it's more about how you feel now, then how you felt then. Anxiety lives in the past and the future, usually it's our own brains that bring it into the now. Learning to ride those waves is key to reaching the shore safely.

Absolutely crazy week mentally, i can't even tell ya, happy it's all over and I feel like myself again. Mental health doesn't have to be a thing you battle on your own. Sometimes hearing someone tell you what you already know can help, don't be afraid to reach out to people in your circle. 

And don't forget, it's OK, to not be ok, even yer boy Reets has his ups and downs sometimes ♡

Today, im honored to announce, probably the greatest award I've ever received in my entire life, never mind career. 

To celebrate 70 years of Portuguese/Canadian diplomacy, the Embassy of Portugal enlisted historian and university professor Dr.Gilberto Fernandes to choose the 70 most influential Portuguese Canadians of the past 70 years. And to my surprise, he selected me to be apart of the 70. 

One of the greatest surprises came when he asked me if I would like to donate my jean vest to the exhibit to be showcased at Toronto Metro Hall as part of the Portuguese Canadian History Exhibit. 

My vest? The same vest that has pen stains, hash holes, and stinks of weed?? THAT VEST?? 

And Dr. Fernandes said, "Yes, that exact one, it represents you so well, it would be an honor to add it to our collection" 

I nearly cried... OK, I did. BUT WHO EVER THOUGHT MY STINKY JEAN VEST WOULD BE APART OF A HISTORIC EXHIBIT!?

Thank you to everyone who's been sending in recommendations of stuff to see, I got a ton of people who said to visit Alcobaça and man they were absolutely right. The sheer size of this monastery was already pretty great but when we went inside and saw the architecture I was blown away. 

When you visit these ancient structures you instantly have a better understanding of how the church and religion got such a strong hold on Portuguese society. 

Imagine you grew up poor, in a little home with crumbling walls and little to no food or money. Then you visit a place like this and see the abundance, the size and most importantly the wealth. You'd also want to dedicate your life to God in hopes that he would bless you or your family with some of these riches. 

Religion may have its flaws, but it's power over humankind has also pushed us forward in many ways, I didn't really appreciate it until this trip, seeing these beautiful holy places puts into perspective how powerful God and belief could be.

Most Portuguese Kids are born into 3 main families. 

 You're either born into a Benfica, Porto, or Sporting family. Whatever happens in life there's nothing worse then being born into a family that cheers for Braga or one of the other B list teams in Portugal.

If you're lucky enough to be born into one of the 3 main teams, you'll be blessed to have a dad who only either owns things that are Red, Blue or Green. I have yet to meet a die hard Benfica fan that owns anything Blue. If it ain't red, it ain't allowed in the house. 

Being born into a Benfica family, I was surrounded by  eagles, little soccer players with pull string dicks and shot cups all with the Benfica logo. 

I've seen family members nearly kill each other over the suggestion that opposing teams are paying off the ref. Ask any Benfica fan and Porto has owned the refs since 1978. Ask any Porto fan and they'll tell you the league pushes for Benfica to win for better profits. 

It's a tale as old as time. 

Yesterday, I lived out a childhood dream of watching a Benfica game live, got to chant and clap and yell 

SLB ! SLB SLB SLB !! 

I watched little kids yell out things I wouldn't whisper to my friends, I watched people smoke cigarettes right in their seat during the game! 

Imagine being at the skydome and during the 7th inning stretch just lighting up a smoke in your seats.... wild.

As you drive around the island you see literally 1000s of cows just living their best lives, munching, moo'in and poo'in.

1 more thing. And this one is just as important as all the nice stuff I wrote above, 

A special thanks goes to all the Portuguese community who said what I did was an embarrassment, who said what i did on stage was a disgrace. People who looked my parents in the eyes and said " He shouldn't be saying those things about us they make us look bad"

"Without love there is no passion, without the hate, there is no flame."

Brought my daughter Aleeya out to the show last night and on the way to the show she kept asking if she could go on stage and I kept saying we'll see.

I go, ok, if I'm gonna bring you up on stage, you gotta have a joke ready, so we make up this little plan where I set her up and she drops a solid little kid punchline.

 I tell her "At the end of dad's set, I'm gonna look sidestage and ill bring you up"

And in the most confident and excited 6 year old voice you could imagine she goes :

"IM READY DAD!! ILL BE WAITING!"

Fast forward a bit, I finish doing my last joke, as I'm thanking the audience, I look side stage by the stairs, there's Aleeya, waiting, I give her the nod and she comes on stage, both hands in the air, waving, like she's a special guest star, and in a way, she was lol 

She comes on, we kick into the bit, Whats your name? How old are you? Do you like dad ? What's your favorite thing about dad ? And she answered them all naturally and with a funny little charm and then, the set up. I ask her, "what's something dad does alot of or all the time?"

And like a 50 year pro of the stage, my little 6 year old goes :

"Dad spends to much time on the toilet, POOPING!" 

BAM! THE WHOLE THEATRE GOES OFF! GIANT LAUGHS ALL AROUND ! 

I quickly grab the mic and pretend she embarrassed me and shoo her off the stage, as she walks off, again, 2 hands in the air, waving to the crowd like she's Dolly Parton..... I could have cried right there. 

As the audience is still laughing and cheering on Aleeya I bring on Shaun Majumder to this lava hot audience!! I step off stage and she runs up and crushes me.... the biggest hug I've ever gotten from her and she says, AND I QUOTE ! 

"THAT WAS AMAZING DAD, I THINK I EVEN GOT BIGGER LAUGHS THEN YOU!!!" 

What a life, what a night. 

Thank you to @shaunmajumder for letting me come on this tour and for allowing me this opportunity. It's a night I'll never forget. 

Now I gotta bring her to an open mic so she can learn how hard it is to get laughs when dad isn't setting her up with gold!
